04916nam a2200757Ia 9780271094991DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710949917 a10.1515/97802710949912doi  a(DE-B1597)678856  a(OCoLC)1419788671  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0150302bisacsh04a133.4/30942qOCoLC222/eng/202404171 aWright, Sharon Hubbs, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEveryday Magicians :bLegal Records and Magic Manuscripts from Tudor England /cSharon Hubbs Wright, Frank Klaassen. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2023] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (164 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMagic in History Sourcebooks00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The God of Norfolk: Prognostication and Other Cunning -- tChapter 2 Theft Divination and the Return of Stolen Goods -- tChapter 3 Love Magic -- tChapter 4 Men’s Games: Gambling, Hunting, and Fishing -- tChapter 5 Healing and Protection from Harm -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Words of Power with Known Meanings -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost of the women and men who practiced magic in Tudor England were not hanged or burned as witches, despite being active members of their communities. These everyday magicians responded to common human problems such as the vagaries of money, love, property, and influence, and they were essential to the smooth functioning of English society. This illuminating book tells their stories through the legal texts in which they are named and the magic books that record their practices.In legal terms, their magic fell into the category of sin or petty crime, the sort that appeared in the lower courts and most often in church courts. Despite their relatively lowly status, scripts for the sorts of magic they practiced were recorded in contemporary manuscripts. Juxtaposing and contextualizing the legal and magic manuscript records creates an unusually rich field to explore the social aspects of magic practice. Expertly constructed for both classroom use and independent study, this book presents in modern English the legal documents and magic texts relevant to ordinary forms of magic practiced in Tudor England. These are accompanied by scholarly introductions with original perspectives on the subjects. Topics covered include: the London cunning man Robert Allen; magic to identify thieves; love magic; magic for hunting, fishing and gambling, and magic for healing and protection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Tudor & Elizabethan Era (1485-1603).2bisacsh  aLearned magic.  aRobert Allen.  aTudor England.  acommon magic.  ademon conjuring.  ahealing magic.  alove magic.  amagic and society.  amagic and the law.  amanuscripts of magic.  anecromancy.  aprotection magic.  asixteenth century.  atheft magic.  awomen and magic.1 aKlaassen, Frank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271094991?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271094991423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271094991/original  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PAC